00:08.620 --> 00:12.540
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.160 --> 00:33.500
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

00:36.120 --> 00:37.840
And here are your hosts.

00:42.540 --> 00:50.080
This is Bill Vernon and David Crews. George Zebrowski is a young science fiction
writer and editor with four novels, a short story collection, and two

00:50.080 --> 00:58.840
anthologies to his credit. His work is characterized by its serious, thoughtful
approach to writing and a novel execution of ideas. Zebrowski's formal academic

00:58.840 --> 01:08.280
training is in philosophy. We asked him why, with this background, he chose to
write science fiction. It seemed to me that science fiction always seemed the

01:08.280 --> 01:23.220
natural kind of writing. I grew up reading science fiction, and its materials
and the kinds of possibilities that it opened up to myself as a reader seem to

01:23.220 --> 01:37.060
belong peculiarly to this time, as opposed to the feeling I got when I read
Charles Dickens or the 19th century writers, aside from Wells, of course, who

01:37.060 --> 01:56.820
straddled both centuries. It seemed to belong uniquely to the 20th century. Of
course, I didn't think about it that way. That came much later. One of

01:56.820 --> 02:05.280
the elements that usually typifies definitions of science fiction is that it is
a literature of ideas. When we asked Zebrowski how philosophical ideas have been

02:05.280 --> 02:16.780
handled in science fiction, he indicated that the approach has generally been
superficial. Well, it's skin deep, and this is surprising, possibly, to a

02:16.780 --> 02:27.000
literature that professes to be a literature of ideas, and yet two areas,
philosophy and cosmology, seem to be very poorly represented, even though you

02:27.000 --> 02:38.480
would think that science fiction would cover these fields in a very deep
fashion. But this is not really surprising. Most fiction, most literature does

02:38.480 --> 02:49.760
not use philosophy in any original sense. What I mean is that philosophy is
usually derived from somewhere else, from some thinker, and then is simply put

02:49.760 --> 02:55.200
to some use as background in a science fiction story or even in a contemporary
novel.

02:57.900 --> 03:09.040
Most writers are not original thinkers in this regard. Even Stapledon, who is
the most overtly philosophical of science fiction writers, is clearly a

03:09.040 --> 03:23.180
Spinozist, following the philosophy of Spinoza, a kind of pantheism. There is
not any original philosophizing going on. Of course, it would be ideal if you

03:23.180 --> 03:35.220
could have a science fiction writer who would be an original thinker and would
present original thinking of a philosophical kind in his science fiction. But

03:35.220 --> 03:44.760
then you might say, why doesn't he just write a book of philosophy and then
perhaps use the philosophical, the original philosophical material that he

03:44.760 --> 03:56.280
himself puts forward in his fiction. We asked Zebrowski if any present-day
science fiction writers use this approach. Lem does this to some degree. He's

03:56.280 --> 04:06.860
written philosophical works of enormous size and then used the ideas developed
there for his science fiction. That's very, very rare.

04:19.660 --> 04:31.480
Do writers aim for particular audiences or niches in science fiction? Zebrowski
indicated he does not. Well, I don't particularly aim for any audience. I simply

04:31.480 --> 04:45.960
aim to be clear and to communicate to any reader who can read fiction. The idea
being that such a reader will understand what you have to say. I think I simply

04:45.960 --> 04:54.040
follow the idea of most writers that you have to communicate. More on George
Zebrowski on our next show.

05:01.340 --> 05:09.180
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

05:09.180 --> 05:09.940
Odessa, Texas.

05:49.980 --> 05:53.900
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:09.500 --> 06:14.860
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

06:17.480 --> 06:19.200
And here are your hosts.

06:23.440 --> 06:31.840
This is David Crews and Bill Vernon. Today's show continues the discussion with
science fiction author George Zebrowski. Zebrowski's novels include The Omega

06:31.840 --> 06:40.860
Point and its prequel Ashes and Stars, The Star Web, and the recently published
Macrolife, which we will discuss in detail later. His editing credits include

06:40.860 --> 06:48.980
the anthology Faster Than Light. Zebrowski provided us with many provocative
ideas about the current state of science fiction. For instance, he considers

06:48.980 --> 06:58.380
much of what's published in science fiction unoriginal. Well, if you consider
that science fiction has been anywhere between 10 and 15 percent of all fiction

06:58.380 --> 07:15.960
published, a great number of it, a great amount, is derivative, built on predigested ideas and
predigested plots. A good example takes to the concept of space colonies or the

07:15.960 --> 07:29.940
L-5 society type of thing. It's very often simply been used as just another
place to have an adventure of some kind, or a place to set a murder mystery or a

07:29.940 --> 07:44.260
suspense story of some kind or another. Predigestion seems to be the operative
method of the copiers. Something comes in and it's slightly new and it's not

07:44.260 --> 07:56.440
used for itself. It's used as just another place to have another barbaric
adventure or whatever. It's easier to do this than to be original in each and

07:56.440 --> 08:09.120
every case. And I'm afraid that like many other writers, I wrote what I was most
influenced by. But as you go on, you realize that quite possibly there is a way

08:09.120 --> 08:11.960
of doing things that is a little more original than that.

08:17.400 --> 08:26.520
According to Zebrowski, it may be the marketplace that influences writers to
produce sure-selling, formula-written pieces. Well, the fact is that most

08:26.520 --> 08:37.920
science fiction has a sort of built-in sales potential. A science fiction book
will sell anywhere between 30,000 or 50,000 copies, no matter who wrote it. This

08:37.920 --> 08:48.960
is unfortunate. Most of the best writers of science fiction, however, become
their own genres. Clark, Asimov, Heinlein are genres unto themselves within the

08:48.960 --> 09:01.500
genre. And people will buy the name no matter what they write. This is also
unfortunate, but it is a sign of some progress on the part of the writer. I

09:01.500 --> 09:09.660
think even if you write a fairly experimental kind of book like Macrolife,
because of the built-in potential, there will be a certain number of readers who

09:09.660 --> 09:18.360
will buy it. There will be a smaller number of people who will actually buy it
because they're interested in that kind of thing. Maybe their tastes will be

09:18.360 --> 09:33.380
widened by it. You really can't tell. You just have to do what you really want
to do. You can't simply write to fill a niche in the market. That's what strikes

09:33.380 --> 09:42.560
me as being very cynical in many writers. They do aim for a particular audience,
and they aim to deliver a certain product, and they don't seem to have any other

09:42.560 --> 09:55.360
ambitions. This would be fine if some of these writers were not capable of war,
in which case they're betraying their own abilities. This kind of comment on my

09:55.360 --> 10:07.120
part sounds perhaps very noble to many other writers, and very idealistic, and
they sort of shake their heads in the way that Claggett shook his head at Billy

10:07.120 --> 10:08.040
Budd's innocence.

10:10.800 --> 10:20.460
But that kind of attitude comes out of the environment in which they move, and I
think you can create for yourself an ambitious environment in which you will

10:20.460 --> 10:29.360
produce, or at least have a shot at producing something that will be closer to
what you're capable of doing. On our next show, we will discuss Zebrowski's

10:29.360 --> 10:30.840
ambitious novel, Macrolife.

10:37.800 --> 10:45.600
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

10:45.600 --> 10:46.360
Odessa, Texas.

