11:48.620 --> 11:53.820
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

11:56.660 --> 11:58.180
And here are your hosts.

12:02.740 --> 12:11.540
This is Bill Vernon. And David Crews. Science fiction author George Zebrowski's
first three novels, The Omega Point, Ashes and Stars, and Star Web, are well

12:11.540 --> 12:20.180
-written space operas with overtones of metaphysics, cosmology, and eschatology.
When Zebrowski's fourth novel, Macrolife, was published in hardcover in 1979,

12:20.180 --> 12:28.480
it received rave reviews from such notables as Arthur C. Clarke, Gregory
Benford, and Gerard K. O'Neill. The basic premise of Macrolife is that a

12:28.480 --> 12:36.280
culture cannot reach its full potential unless it leaves the planet on which it
originated or inhabits. Right. Only in self-contained worlds traveling in

12:36.280 --> 12:44.140
interstellar space, or at least in orbit around a planet, can a culture develop
the social systems required for it to flourish? We asked Zebrowski how he

12:44.140 --> 12:53.180
conceived the idea of Macrolife. And I think I read an article by G. Harry
Stein, who was real hard science, kind of buffed, and he complained that all the

12:53.180 --> 13:03.980
really new ideas, this was around 1961, I think, he complained that all the new
ideas were being ignored by science fiction and that the best speculations were

13:03.980 --> 13:15.800
going on in places like General Electric and think tanks and whatever, and the
science fiction writers were 25 years behind the times. So I looked at one of

13:15.800 --> 13:27.140
the ideas he mentioned, which was a concept called Macro Life, two words, by
Dandridge Cole, and this was for something called the Ultimate Human Society.

13:28.080 --> 13:37.380
And Cole made a lot of sense to me, and so I decided then that I was going to
write a novel to be called Macrolife. So Zebrowski took the central premise of

13:37.380 --> 13:50.320
Dandridge Cole's idea in 1961 and shaped it into a vision. Over the years, I
developed the idea much further than he had taken it. His macro worlds were on

13:50.320 --> 14:06.960
the order of the Queen Mary, 10,000 tons, 10,000 ton worldlets, very small,
probably closer to O'Neill's concept of space colonies. My 600-kilometer egg

14:06.960 --> 14:19.600
shapes with dozens of levels and asteroid cores at the center are much more
ambitious than anything Cole came up with. And also my primary interest was in

14:19.600 --> 14:29.320
the kind of social systems that might develop within this material container,
because you could have almost any kind of social system you want developing

14:29.320 --> 14:46.080
within the economic supports that are provided by this concept of Macrolife,
the kind of self-reproducing mobile space colony that is in effect a form of

14:46.080 --> 14:57.020
life. It moves, it reproduces, it thinks with its human social component. What
does Zebrowski propose would happen if one of the Macrolife units were to

14:57.020 --> 15:06.980
become too heavily populated, or if a disagreement were to develop? Listen as he
explains the possibilities. The possibilities seem endless, especially for

15:06.980 --> 15:21.720
something like the idea of revolt within the human generations. Whenever people
would get to the point of dissatisfaction with a particular system they have,

15:21.780 --> 15:37.840
they would simply create another macro world container using the resources and
help of the parent, create their own society within it. It seems to me that this

15:37.840 --> 15:50.260
would give the kind of conservatism and stability that is demanded by human
beings in a social system, as well as the openness and sense of creativity and

15:50.260 --> 16:05.340
adventure that seems to be lacking from social systems that become too old and
don't want to change. It seems to be an answer to the problem of what is life

16:05.340 --> 16:09.520
for. More on George Zebrowski's Macrolife on our next show.

16:16.520 --> 16:24.460
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

16:24.460 --> 16:30.520
Odessa, Texas. 

17:08.440 --> 17:12.320
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

17:28.120 --> 17:33.340
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

17:36.080 --> 17:37.660
And here are your hosts.

17:42.180 --> 17:50.660
This is David Crews. And Bill Vernon. George Zebrowski's epic science fiction
novel, Macrolife, proposes the idea that cultures must leave their dirt worlds

17:50.660 --> 17:59.800
in order to develop fully. We asked Zebrowski why he feels a culture cannot
develop fully when it is constrained to a planet's surface. If the resources of

17:59.800 --> 18:15.120
a planet are limited and it has no space-based industry with which to supplement
the finitudes of a planetary surface, then I think the culture will suffer

18:15.120 --> 18:28.920
primarily because of the finitude. As I said, an open, exploration-oriented,
knowledge-oriented Renaissance culture deposits a different kind of world in the

18:28.920 --> 18:41.680
human heart. A limited culture deposits an ecological 60s kind of approach in
the human heart. And I think there's a sense of constriction that would develop.

18:42.380 --> 18:56.160
Take the idea of a zero-growth society. I see that as essentially static, both
materially and culturally in the long run. It would reach a kind of equilibrium

18:56.160 --> 19:09.420
with its environment, recycling everything. And that would be the end, I would
think, of that kind of culture. The idea of such space colonies has appeared in

19:09.420 --> 19:19.380
science fiction, though rarely. But certainly no writer has developed it on the
scale that Zebrowski has. Now there are Macrolife-like books within the field.

19:20.080 --> 19:32.820
Cities in Flight by James Blish is sort of like that. But the cities don't
reproduce. They are old earth cities that simply have taken to wandering around.

19:33.960 --> 19:45.640
It's proto-Macrolife of one kind or another. The ideas have been around, but
the kind of coherent sociocultural approach that I think I've taken in that

19:45.640 --> 19:58.220
book, which will be the basis of at least six or seven other novels, each are
vastly different in technique and form from Macrolife. It just has not been

19:58.220 --> 20:08.720
copied by anybody. The appeal of Macrolife is that the idea of such grandiose
space colonies, as fleshed out by Zebrowski, is new. It is not a rehashed theme.

20:09.000 --> 20:21.040
In fact, Zebrowski feels the idea may be slow to catch on. Most science fiction
writers still don't see it. They still feel that we're going to colonize planets

20:21.040 --> 20:33.120
on a large scale, and I'm afraid that's a very old imperialistic idea of
colonizing. I think there will be people who will attempt to do something with

20:33.120 --> 20:46.120
planets, especially if we develop terraforming techniques, say, for the
transformation of Venus or the Moon. That sort of thing will go on, but frankly,

20:46.480 --> 20:59.620
it's very difficult. It all depends how much energy you have to play around
with, but going to find solar-like planets in other star systems and taking them

20:59.620 --> 21:12.720
over, that really strikes me as a kind of abortion of possible life to come.
That a culture must flee its planet and go into space to bloom, Zebrowski

21:12.720 --> 21:22.560
believes, flies in the face of a long tradition in science fiction. It, of
course, destroys a whole generation of science fictional concepts which demand

21:22.560 --> 21:36.140
that we colonize the planets of other solar systems where I feel if it were
possible to do that, native life might be developing or might one day develop,

21:36.280 --> 21:50.320
and we would be preempting possible biological evolution there. This preempts
all that kind of science fiction and, in fact, says that that'll never happen. A

21:50.320 --> 21:59.660
whole science fictional universe dies if you take Macrolife seriously. George
Zebrowski and the old master, John Campbell, on our next show.

22:06.780 --> 22:14.600
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

22:14.600 --> 22:37.520
Odessa, Texas. 

22:59.840 --> 23:03.740
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

23:19.420 --> 23:24.740
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

23:27.420 --> 23:29.120
And here are your hosts.

23:33.380 --> 23:42.720
This is Bill Vernon. And David Crews. Science fiction writer George Zebrowski,
still in his 30s, has produced a monumental novel, Macrolife, whose style,

23:42.940 --> 23:51.040
scope, and originality will surely influence science fiction for years. John W.
Campbell, Jr. has his indelible stamp on the field of science fiction, primarily

23:51.040 --> 24:00.560
through his 34-year editorship of the magazine Astounding Stories. Zebrowski
actually met Campbell shortly before his death in 1971. We asked him to tell us

24:00.560 --> 24:12.400
a bit about the meeting. I spent six hours in his office, I think it was in
1970, just a year or so before his death. I don't remember the exact date. It

24:12.400 --> 24:26.020
was quite an experience. I think I can sum up Campbell's attitude. He was
sitting behind his desk puffing away on his cigarette holder, very anxious to

24:26.020 --> 24:36.020
have a discussion that would not be him agreeing with me or me agreeing with
him. He picked up a copy, I think, of Orbit by Damon Knight and a copy of

24:36.020 --> 24:46.380
fantasy and science fiction. And he said the interesting thing is the writers in
these two books write beautifully, but they don't think very much. And he said

24:46.380 --> 24:54.520
the great problem of science fiction is you have people who write beautifully
and don't think, and you have people who think gorgeously and can't write. So I

24:54.520 --> 25:08.580
was very impressed with Campbell. And he valued disagreement above easy
agreement. He told me, if you agree with me, I'll change my mind. Some consider

25:08.580 --> 25:16.500
Campbell's influence on science fiction, which bordered on actual dominance
during the 1940s, as a positive development. Others view his contributions with

25:16.500 --> 25:24.880
misgiving. We asked Zebrowski his opinion on the value of Campbell's influence.
His added comments are interesting. I think it was positive, and I think his

25:24.880 --> 25:38.900
disciples do not make the best case for him. They do not represent his ideas.
And I think that it's the worst of John Campbell's effect on writers and on the

25:38.900 --> 25:51.960
publishing of science fiction that has come in for deserved attack. The kind of
interpretation of Campbell that makes sense out of Campbell's approach. I think

25:51.960 --> 26:04.900
Greg Benford put it, Campbell basically wanted broader horizons and a deeper
sense of humanity in his writers. And that's the kind of defense that is not

26:04.900 --> 26:15.620
made of John W. Campbell. I think that John Campbell's legitimate heirs are
people like Ursula Le Guin, Gregory Benford, perhaps Arthur C. Clarke, Philip K.

26:15.760 --> 26:29.580
Dick, Gene Wolfe, and the writers who bring a sense of human character into an
area of broader horizons in ideas, in considering the future of science and

26:29.580 --> 26:42.240
technology, in considering many of the softer sciences. I think the people who
defend Campbell along the lines of, you know, let's have more hard science and

26:42.240 --> 26:55.320
engineering in our fiction, don't really understand what he was trying to do. I
think it was James Blish who said that when you say hard science fiction, what

26:55.320 --> 27:08.120
he meant by it is hard science fiction across the board, hard thinking, fine
writing, hard characterization, that unity of values that I alluded to before.

27:09.160 --> 27:22.960
That's what Campbell really pointed to. And of course he failed to bring about
this kind of science fiction, although he had some success. Anybody would have

27:22.960 --> 27:36.860
to fail to some degree, but I think the people who defend Campbell are usually
those who turn off the literary or ambitious writer. A six-hour meeting of the

27:36.860 --> 27:45.380
minds. John Campbell, the man who probably more than anyone else set the stage
for the kind of science fiction being produced today, and George Zebrowski, one

27:45.380 --> 27:48.160
of today's bright stars destined for greater accomplishment.

27:55.680 --> 28:03.580
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

28:03.580 --> 28:08.880
Odessa, Texas.

